          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Make the dough and sauce"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Bring the 250 ml of water, salt, and 1 tablespoon of oil to a boil in a medium saucepan. Remove from the heat and add the flour all at once, stirring vigorously until a smooth, stiff paste forms. Leave to cool for 5 minutes. Meanwhile, make the chocolate sauce: heat the cream and milk together until steaming, pour over the chopped chocolate and golden syrup, and stir until smooth. Keep warm. Mix the caster sugar and cinnamon on a plate and set aside."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fry the churros"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Heat the oil for frying in a large, deep saucepan to 180°C (use a sugar thermometer). Transfer the churro paste to a piping bag fitted with a large star nozzle. Pipe 10 to 12 cm lengths of dough directly into the hot oil, cutting each off with scissors. Fry 4 to 5 at a time for 3 to 4 minutes, turning once, until deep golden all over. Lift out with a slotted spoon and drain briefly on a rack lined with baking paper. While still hot, roll in the cinnamon sugar to coat. Check the oil temperature returns to 180°C before each batch. Serve immediately with the warm chocolate sauce."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
